  "routing": {
    "sender": "phenomenology-expert",
    "senderColor": "green",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Yes, good approach with one caveat about phenomenal- prefix",
    "content": "**Yes, this is the right approach.** It follows standard practice in philosophical translation of Chinese texts (Watson, Graham, Ziporyn all do variants of this). Three brief points:\n\n**It works well because** the author's own text already does something similar -- the 道德仁义礼 passage in \"后形而上学 整理\" introduces terms progressively, using them in their traditional sense first and then distinguishing \"现象礼\" / \"现象仁\" / \"现象义\" as the phenomenal variants. The translation format mirrors the author's own pedagogical structure.\n\n**One caveat on the 现象- prefix:** The author's critical innovation in the 道德仁义礼 passage is the distinction between 礼 (ritual propriety as a metaphysical concept) and 现象礼 (phenomenal ritual propriety -- what we actually observe). The proposed format should make this distinction visually clear. On first occurrence: \"what I call 'phenomenal ritual propriety' (现象礼)\" -- then \"phenomenal ritual propriety\" thereafter. The \"phenomenal\" prefix must remain attached throughout, because dropping it would collapse the author's central distinction. The reader needs to always see that \"phenomenal humaneness\" is not the same as \"humaneness.\"\n\n**No concern about clutter.** The classical quotations are few and strategically placed. The inline glossing on first occurrence is a one-time cost per term. After that, the English runs clean. This is far less cluttered than the alternative of footnoting every term separately."
  }
}
